;</div>\n<div>\n	- Basic knowledge of material and production technique</div>\n<div>\n	- Good sense of form&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	- Good Chinese and English communication skill&nbsp;</div>\n<div>\n	- Good time management skill</div>\n<div>\n	- 3 day&rsquo;s working per week is required, at least 6 months&rsquo; internship is also required</div>\n<div>\n	- University &ndash; grade 3 or Master studying &ndash; grade 2 is prefer</div>\n',20313),(1169,'2014-09-06 19:34:30','2014-09-06 19:34:30','product','null',20314),(1170,'2014-09-06 19:47:15','2014-09-09 02:03:22','head_title','SPIRIT OF BAMBOO, HEART OF CHINA',20315),(1171,'2014-09-06 19:47:15','2014-09-09 02:03:22','head_body','<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">Bamboo wares started when Chinese history was merely a mixture of legends and folklore. Can Cong (Chinese: silk worm man), the legendary forefather of Sichuan people, was born and grew up in Qingshen county. He “taught the locals agriculture and sericulture, and was therefore regarded as God”. At this time Qingshen locals started to use bamboo woven dustpans to breed silk worms. In the Tang dynasty (618-907 AD), bamboo wares prevailed in daily life, from mats, to baskets, to fans. In the Song (906-1279 AD) and Ming dynasties (1368 - 1644 AD) bamboo woven wares were extremely varied, including many different patterns and shapes. Yu Chengxun from Qingshen county, who became an official during the Ming dynasty was selected to enter the Hanlin Academy. When he entered palace service he owned bamboo book cases and food containers that were so exquisitely crafted, they are now collected in the Museum of Chinese Bamboo Artifacts. </span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">\n	Nowadays, craftsmen continue to innovate, building on traditional craftsmanship, inventing new techniques and styles. </p>\n',20315),(1172,'2014-09-06 19:47:15','2014-09-09 02:03:22','product','\"\"',20315),(1173,'2014-09-06 19:51:28','2014-09-09 02:02:53','head_title','MORE PRECIOUS THAN GOLD AND JADE',20316),(1174,'2014-09-06 19:51:28','2014-09-09 02:02:53','head_body','<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">Zitan has been used to make furniture throughout China’s long history. There are records of its use at the end of the Eastern dynasty. (23-200 AD) and there are records of its use at the Tang Dynasty court (618-907 AD). By the Ming dynasty (1368-1644 AD), the court showed a liking for zitan furniture. In the Qing dynasty (1644-1911 AD) zitan entered the court and it became the must have material used by palace workshops to make Qing court furniture and curios. Wealthy aristocratic and merchant families also had furniture and daily objects commissioned in zitan.</span></p>\n',20316),(1175,'2014-09-06 19:51:28','2014-09-09 02:02:53','product','\"\"',20316),(1176,'2014-09-06 19:52:19','2014-09-09 02:03:08','head_title','THIN AS CICADA’S WING, LIGHT AS A DRIFTING CLOUD',20317),(1177,'2014-09-06 19:52:19','2014-09-09 02:03:08','head_body','<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">The Eggshell porcelain technique has existed for almost a thousand years. Before eggshell porcelain shadowy blue and white wares (Yingqingci) had been largely produced in Jingdezhen during the Song Dynasty (960-1279). But it wasn’t until under the Ming Dynasty reign of Wanli (1573-1619) that the famous porcelain master Hao Shijiu invented eggshell cups, creating a unique type of porcelain which required an independent manufacturing technique. From this time on, the technique was named eggshell porcelain.  </span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">\n	Remarkable in their extraordinary thinness, eggshell wares take over 40 processes to make, including mixing ingredients, turning the clay mixture, repairing, smoothing, trimming, drawing and glazing, firing three times, etc. and all by hand.</p>\n',20317),(1178,'2014-09-06 19:52:19','2014-09-09 02:03:08','product','\"\"',20317),(1179,'2014-09-06 19:54:27','2014-09-09 02:02:39','head_title','BODY AND SOUL TOGETHER SEAMLESS CLOTHING',20318),(1180,'2014-09-06 19:54:27','2014-09-09 02:02:39','head_body','<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">Felt making is an ancient technique invented by herdsman to make non-woven cloth. Herdsmen use felt to make their rugs, yurts, clothing and cooking utensils. As nomadic peoples used these skills used to make yurts, the same skills, combined with original innovative designs, are used to create seamless felted cashmere one-off and unique garments with no stitching.</span></p>\n',20318),(1181,'2014-09-06 19:54:27','2014-09-09 02:02:39','product','\"\"',20318),(1182,'2014-09-06 19:55:50','2014-09-06 22:18:04','head_title','抓绒',20319),(1183,'2014-09-06 19:55:50','2014-09-06 22:18:04','head_body','<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">游牧人最古老的发明之一是制作厚实的毡子的工艺。他们用毡子装饰布置房间、制作衣物及厨房用具。极富巧思的设计师配合技艺娴熟的匠人，将原先游牧民族用羊毛制作蒙古包的工艺，用来制作羊绒毡服，一整件衣服，没有拼缝，没有针脚，宛若天成。</span></p>\n',20319),(1184,'2014-09-06 19:55:50','2014-09-06 22:18:05','product','\"\"',20319),(1185,'2014-09-06 19:56:37','2014-09-06 20:06:50','head_title','薄如蝉翼 轻如浮云',20320),(1186,'2014-09-06 19:56:37','2014-09-06 20:06:50','head_body','<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">景德镇的薄胎瓷烧制，有近千年的历史。北宋时，景德镇大量烧造的影青瓷，滋润透影，薄而轻巧。但直至明代万历年间昊十九发明的卵幕杯，才得以让薄胎作为一种单独的制瓷工艺，从一般制瓷技艺中独立出来。影青瓷也自此有了一个专门的名词——薄胎工艺，薄如蛋壳的薄胎瓷制作从配料、拉坯、利坯（修坯）、上釉到绘画、烧制，须经四十多道工序，全部采用手工，分三次烧成。</span></p>\n',20320),(1187,'2014-09-06 19:56:37','2014-09-06 20:06:50','product','\"null\"',20320),(1188,'2014-09-06 19:57:27','2014-09-06 22:37:12','head_title','百年成材 木比金玉',20321),(1189,'2014-09-06 19:57:28','2014-09-06 22:37:12','head_body','<p class=\"p1\">\n	我国古代使用紫檀木制作器物历史悠久，东汉末年已见于记载，唐代宫廷中亦有使用紫檀木的记录。至明代，紫檀木受到皇家的宠爱。清代，紫檀木大量进入宫廷中，为内务府造办处用于制作清宫家具及文玩之器的必备材料，同时一些富商大贾之家也多使用名贵的紫檀木制造家具及生活用品。</p>\n',20321),(1190,'2014-09-06 19:57:28','2014-09-06 22:37:12','product','\"\"',20321),(1191,'2014-09-06 20:00:06','2014-09-06 22:24:16','head_title','',20322),(1192,'2014-09-06 20:00:06','2014-09-06 22:24:16','head_body','<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">张老师打着赤膊，捻着竹丝，揣摩着心中那一张纵横交错的图谱。无论是教学还是实践，他一辈子的心思都在想要摆脱竹编的匠气。编织再怎么绚丽，都只是一个编织游戏，工艺娴熟后，只剩下匠气。</span></p>\n',20322),(1193,'2014-09-06 20:00:06','2014-09-06 22:24:16','product','\"\"',20322),(1194,'2014-09-06 20:23:50','2014-09-09 16:42:05','location','beijing',20323),(1195,'2014-09-06 20:23:50','2014-09-09 16:42:05','address','<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">SB107B, B1 China World Mall, China World Trade Center 1, Jianguomen Waidajie, Beijing, 100001, PRC</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">Tel: +86-10-6505-7358</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">shangxia.bj1@shang-xia.com</span></p>\n',20323),(1196,'2014-09-06 20:23:50','2014-09-09 16:42:05','latlng','116.465016,39.915016',20323),(1197,'2014-09-06 20:23:50','2014-09-09 16:42:05','info_title','BEIJING: THE SECOND SHANG XIA BOUTIQUE',20323),(1198,'2014-09-06 20:32:07','2014-09-09 17:39:56','location','paris',20324),(1199,'2014-09-06 20:32:07','2014-09-09 17:39:56','address','<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">8 Sèvres Road, 75006 Paris, France</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">Tel: +33-1-42-22-53-62</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">Fax: +33-1-42-22-58-03</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">sevres.paris@shang-xia.com</span></p>\n',20324),(1200,'2014-09-06 20:32:07','2014-09-09 17:39:56','latlng','48.8520134,2.3288802',20324),(1201,'2014-09-06 20:32:07','2014-09-09 17:39:56','info_title','PARIS: THE FIRST EUROPEAN SHANG XIA BOUTIQUE',20324),(1202,'2014-09-06 20:32:56','2014-09-09 09:46:25','location','shanghai',20325),(1203,'2014-09-06 20:32:56','2014-09-09 09:46:25','address','<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">Add: 1F, South Tower, Hong Kong Plaza, 283 Huaihai Middle Rd, Shanghai, 200021, PRC</span></p>\n<p class=\"p2\">\n	 </p>\n<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">Tel: +86-21-6390 8899</span></p>\n<p class=\"p1\">\n	<span class=\"s1\">shangxia.sh1@shang-xia.com</span></p>\n',20325),(1204,'2014-09-06 20:32:56','2014-09-09 09:46:25','latlng','121.47906,31.228104',20325),(1205,'2014-09-06 20:32:56','2